data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** — they run directly as SQL without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement, no entities loaded
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
        s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement, no entities loaded
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is fast:**
- Generates a single `UPDATE`/`DELETE` SQL statement executed server-side
- **Zero entities loaded into memory** (no `ToListAsync`, no change tracking)
- 500K updates or 2M deletes happen entirely in the database

**Caveats:**
- These bypass the change tracker — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the change
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed (or wanted)
- If 2M deletes causes lock escalation/timeouts, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
